WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6 New Year's English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Do you enjoy eating noodles, Beth?

6
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.000
I love noodles, yes.

7
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.000
I think my favorite are udon, the big thick ones.

8
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Mmm, the so good.

9
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Well, some people buy them dried in a packet.

10
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Others make them fresh from wheat or rice.

11
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
But there is little doubts that noodles are popular around the world.

12
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.000
From their origins, probably somewhere in China,

13
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Neudal recipes were spread by traders on the ancient Silk Road.

14
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
At each destination, along the road, people gave noodles a twist

15
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
adding different flavors and ingredients to create a new dish.

16
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
In this program, we'll visit the United States and Japan,

17
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:58.000
two countries which have taken noodles and created exciting new varieties.

18
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
As usual, we'll learn some useful new vocabulary.

19
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
And remember, you can read along with the transcript of this program,

20
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.000
available now on our website, bbclearningenglish.com.

21
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.000
But first, Neil, I have a question for you,

22
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:17.000
as well as different shapes and ingredients, noodles come in many different flavors.

23
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
So which region of China is famous for its spicy flavors?

24
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Is it a Shanghai?

25
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.000
B, Sichuan? Or C, Guangzhou?

26
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Well, I think actually best.

27
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
I know the answer to this, but I've been lucky enough to have been to this place.

28
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
I think it's B, Sichuan.

29
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:41.000
Okay, well, you sound confident.

30
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.000
I will reveal the answer later in the program.

31
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:47.000
Bbc World Service program, the Food Chain,

32
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
investigated how noodles spread from Asia through Europe to America.

33
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:58.000
They uncovered a surprising story that pasta comes from noodles brought back to Italy

34
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
by Marco Polo in the 13th century.

35
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Jan Lennu, author of the book on the Nudel Road,

36
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
doesn't believe this story.

37
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:13.000
So noodles were very exotic in the 1920s and 30s in the United States.

38
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And there was a new pasta association in America that wanted to promote the manufacturing of

39
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
dried pasta.

40
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And so they came up with a story about how Marco Polo went to China and found the noodle there

41
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
and brought it all the way to Italy.

42
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.000
In the 1920s, noodles were popular because they were exotic,

43
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.000
meaning foreign, unusual and exciting.

44
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:45.000
At that time, pasta companies were promoting a new invention, dried pasta.

45
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.000
So they came up with a story about Marco Polo to sell more pasta.

46
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.000
If you come up with something, you suggest or think up an idea.

47
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And it worked.

48
00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Sales have passed a jump as a result.

49
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Now our second destination, Japan, also has a history of eating noodles.

50
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
One of the most famous Japanese noodle dishes is ramen.

51
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And Frank Stregle, a blogger living in Tokyo, knows all about it.

52
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:15.000
He eats over 300 bowls of ramen a year.

53
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:21.000
He explained to BBC World Services the food chain how Chinese immigrants to Japan

54
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
in the late 1800s influenced this Japanese dish.

55
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:31.000
And at one point or another, different chefs decided to localise these dishes.

56
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.000
They said, we love these Chinese noodle dishes.

57
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.000
However, why don't we tweak them?

58
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Why don't we make them a little bit more Japanese?

59
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Frank says that at one point or another,

60
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Chef started to make noodle dishes more Japanese.

61
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Here, the phrase at one point or another means at some unspecified time in the past.

62
00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.000
They did this by tweaking Chinese noodles.

63
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
In other words, by changing them slightly to make them better.

64
00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Different, or in this case, more Japanese.

65
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
By making these tweaks, adding new toppings and slices of beef or chicken,

66
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Japanese chefs created the noodle dish we know today as ramen.

67
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Here's Frank Stregle again, talking with BBC World Services, the food chain.

68
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:20.000
And what I find fascinating about ramen compared to perhaps other wonderful noodle dishes around the world is that ramen continues to evolve.

69
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
Unlike other Japanese foods, it's okay to push the boundaries.

70
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Frank thinks that Japanese ramen continues to evolve to develop and change gradually in response to new developments and ideas.

71
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:39.000
Unlike other traditional foods such as sushi, modern versions of ramen push the boundaries.

72
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.000
If you push the boundaries, you act in a way which challenges normal, acceptable behavior.

73
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:52.000
Yes, noodles have changed so much since ancient times that today you can buy them dried in a packet and simply add hot water.

74
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
But the flavors and the noodles themselves maintain a link to the past.

75
00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Now speaking of flavors, what was the answer to your question, bet?

76
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Well, I asked you which region of China is famous for its spicy flavors?

77
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:10.000
You are very confident with saying, Sishwan and that is the correct answer.

78
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Sishwan is a place that is famous for spicy food such as the Sishwan pepper and Sishwan hot pot.

79
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Okay, it's time to recap the vocabulary we've learnt.

80
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:27.000
If you give something a twist, you change it in some small way to create something new and exciting.

81
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:33.000
The adjective exotic means unusual and exciting because of coming from far away.

82
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.000
The phrase at one point or another means at some unspecified time in the past.

83
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
If you tweak something, you alter it slightly in order to improve it.

84
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Something which evolves, develops and changes gradually.

85
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And finally, the idiom to push the boundaries means to do things which challenge normal acceptable behavior.

86
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

87
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:02.000
If you enjoyed the program, why not visit our website and check out all of the different podcasts that we have at BBC Learning English.

88
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
There's something there for everyone.

89
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Thanks for joining us and goodbye.

90
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.000
Bye!
